Gills finely serrate (fimbriate?). The white drops might be white spores captured in water.
Spore print bright white, heavy.
No bruising or odor was noted.

results.notes:
- Mushroomy smell. No hints of curry from what I could tell.
- Taste not bitter, pleasant
- Pores of older mushrooms nearby were 5-6mm deep.

The only thing throwing me off is that the older specimens caps didnt really flash blue when ammonia was applied.

results.notes:
Single specimen found near the trunk of an eastern white pine (Pinus strobus) in a cluster of pine trees at perimeter of small grass field.

Dimensions:
Cap diameter 15.2 cm.
Stipe length 15.4 cm, excluding underground swollen base of 2.7 cm.
Stipe diameter narrows from 3.2 cm at base to 2.1 cm at apex.

Cap was covered with brown-yellow-orange scales.

The cap had not expanded at the time of collocation. I put the base of the specimen in water overnight and the cap opened to reveal light brown gills, which subsequently progressed to dark brown.

The partial veil was very thick, robust.

No odor was detected at time of collection, but almond odor was observed in later examination after bisecting the stipe.

Bisecting the stipe confirmed that it was hollow stuffed. KOH on pileus, stipe and context of stipe produced a yellow reaction (fainter on the cap, perhaps because it was somewhat dry). Also noted reddening of interior of stipe on exposure.

Typical A. campestris have been observed in an adjacent grass field in prior years. One almond scented Agaricus was found about 13 years ago in a median strip across the street from this pine stand (https://mushroomobserver.org/45991?q=1oyLM). That specimen was not similar – cap was white, with no scales, and partial veil was not as robust.
See https://mushroomobserver.org/names/59447?q=1oyLM for description of A. nanaugustus.

This appears to be the first observation of this species in Maryland, though there have been observations in adjacent states (DC, Virginia, West Virginia and Pennsylvania).

Will attempt to sequence this specimen to confirm ID.

results.notes:
Growing on a sun-exposed edge of pine-oak barrens along Coopers Rd. halfway between Pakim Pond and the campground sites. The conditions have been very dry lately, so this collection came as a total surprise.
The bleached out fruitbodies were still showing the dark lavender-violaceus color on the inner stipe surface at the apex hidden from the sun. The taste was decidedly bitter.
Both basidiomata had substantial larval damage, particularly in the stipes; the lesser-affected fruitbody (thicker stipe, oval cap) was preserved and will be submitted for ITS sequencing.
I think it’s the same entity as obs 27199, obs 75191, obs 289422 and obs 336682, all observed in the NJ Pine Barrens. As a matter of fact, #27199 was growing about a 1/4 mile to the west of the present collection, also on the edge of Coopers Rd., so it could be the same organism.
It remains to be seen if this violatinctus suspect is identical to T. violatinctus growing in deciduous and mixed upland forests of NJ: obs 210716, obs 288468 (saved) and obs 462953.

Found 7/26/23, many of them growing on the side of a well-rotted hardwood log in the woods near Lake Lemon, IN. Found again on 8/7/2023, after some rain and cooler weather; several younger specimens among the older ones as described below.
Caps: In younger specimens: maroon red, convex with small central dimple; most with patches of tiny grayish scales peripherally, and some with a central patch of the tiny gray scales. Older specimens: Caps dark red-brown peripherally, centers darker (almost black) or in some cases reddish, becoming light gray-brown as they dry, with fine light taupe scales. Up to 4 cm diameter, convex to plane. Flesh thin. Odor unremarkable. KOH on cap: Turned immediately red-black, with blue-black zone around the drop.
Gills: crowded, attached, same color as cap in younger specimens, but in older specimens the gills are paler than the cap: pinkish-red-brown.
Stalks red-brown, short, curved to root in the side of the log. Hollow. Up to 2.5 cm long, 4 mm wide. No ring.
Spore print white.
Spores: oval with projecting attachment pore, smooth walled, large nucleus visible. 4.4-6.5 × 3.2-4.9 microns.
Staining reaction with Melzers: mildly amyloid?
